1
00:00:01,177 --> 00:00:29,396
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:30,152 --> 00:00:34,340
Homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:37,085 --> 00:00:48,484
So now, what I'm going to try and do is give you the full panoramic view of the Theravada process of enlightenment, the actual practice.

4
00:00:49,726 --> 00:00:54,354
Not so much the theory, the theories behind it, but exactly what the practice is.

5
00:01:01,557 --> 00:01:06,486
Interestingly enough, it's not based directly on the Buddha's teaching.

6
00:01:08,569 --> 00:01:26,079
It so happened that a certain monk called Punnamantaniputta,

7
00:01:27,646 --> 00:01:33,873
His name would be Punna, the son of Mantani, like Sariputta, called after your mother.

8
00:01:35,875 --> 00:01:39,879
And he's been heard of as being a very good, he's understood the Dharma.

9
00:01:40,780 --> 00:01:42,361
So Sariputta goes off to see him.

10
00:01:42,942 --> 00:01:47,668
And they don't know each other, or rather Sariputta knows him, he doesn't know Sariputta.

11
00:01:47,688 --> 00:01:53,433
And Sariputta puts him to these questions, you see, and asks him, what's his understanding of the Dharma?

12
00:02:00,096 --> 00:02:01,905
And I'll read this simile first.

13
00:02:02,709 --> 00:02:06,123
As to that friend, in other words, how does one attain nirvana?

14
00:02:06,290 --> 00:02:11,318
I shall give you a simile, for some wise men understand the meaning of a statement by means of a simile.

15
00:02:12,158 --> 00:02:23,836
Suppose that King Pasenadi of Kursala, while living in Sarvati, had some urgent business to settle in Sakata, and that between Sarvati and Sakata seven relay chariots were kept ready for him.

16
00:02:24,236 --> 00:02:35,554
Then King Pasenadi of Kursala, leaving Sarvati through the inner palace door, would mount the first chariot, and by means of the first relay chariot he would arrive at the second relay chariot.

17
00:02:35,905 --> 00:02:39,329
Then he would dismount from the first chariot and mount the second chariot.

18
00:02:39,830 --> 00:02:46,598
And by means of the second chariot he would arrive at the third chariot.

19
00:02:46,617 --> 00:02:49,622
By means of the third chariot he would arrive at the fourth.

20
00:02:49,641 --> 00:02:52,866
Very exciting stuff.

21
00:02:52,885 --> 00:02:55,990
Finally, of course, he does actually get to the seventh chariot.

22
00:02:57,235 --> 00:03:01,219
And by means of the seventh chariot, he would arrive at the inner palace door of Saqqata.

23
00:03:01,520 --> 00:03:13,715
Then, when he had come into the inner palace door, his friends and acquaintances, his kinsmen and relatives would ask him, Sire, did you come from Sabati to the inner palace door in Saqqata by means of this relay chariot?

24
00:03:14,616 --> 00:03:18,460
How then should King Pashtunari of Kosala answer in order to answer correctly?

25
00:03:18,500 --> 00:03:20,462
And it's told us again.

26
00:03:22,384 --> 00:03:23,225
So now,

27
00:03:24,590 --> 00:03:27,153
When he talks about these chariots, he talks about this.

28
00:03:28,256 --> 00:03:34,727
Purification of virtue is for the sake of reaching purification of mind.

29
00:03:36,068 --> 00:03:40,456
Purification of mind is for the sake of reaching purification of view.

30
00:03:41,679 --> 00:03:45,906
Purification of view is for the sake of reaching purification of mind.

31
00:03:46,443 --> 00:03:47,745
by overcoming doubt.

32
00:03:48,485 --> 00:03:56,718
Purification by overcoming doubt is for the sake of reaching purification by knowledge and vision of what is the path and what is not the path.

33
00:03:57,941 --> 00:04:06,394
Purification by knowledge and vision of what is the path and what is not the path is for the sake of reaching purification of knowledge and vision of the way.

34
00:04:07,276 --> 00:04:14,627
Purification by knowledge and vision of the way is for the sake of reaching purification by knowledge and vision

35
00:04:15,062 --> 00:04:20,752
Purification by knowledge and vision is for the sake of reaching final nirvana without clinging.

36
00:04:21,072 --> 00:04:26,961
It is for the sake of final nirvana without clinging that the Holy One has lived under the Blessed One.

37
00:04:29,586 --> 00:04:30,247
Need I explain?

38
00:04:33,872 --> 00:04:34,252
So,

39
00:04:35,752 --> 00:04:50,911
This particular system of explaining the Dhamma, the Buddha acknowledged it as being very good, was used most successfully by Buddhaghosa.

40
00:04:50,951 --> 00:04:57,798
Well, first of all, it's Upatissa, which was 3rd century AD, or Common Era.

41
00:04:58,379 --> 00:05:00,341
And his book is called The Path of Freedom.

42
00:05:01,047 --> 00:05:03,514
It got lost and it only existed in the Chinese.

43
00:05:03,653 --> 00:05:10,112
And as far as I know, it helped to revive Buddhism in Tibet through Asita, who found the book.

44
00:05:11,576 --> 00:05:15,326
It was only recently translated from the Chinese back into English.

45
00:05:15,862 --> 00:05:25,737
But who took that system and made it into what must be one of the great world classics of spiritual manual is Buddhaghosa.

46
00:05:25,978 --> 00:05:26,699
That's his book.

47
00:05:27,259 --> 00:05:29,543
The Path of Purification.

48
00:05:29,942 --> 00:05:34,649
Very dense, full of all sorts of little exercises.

49
00:05:35,271 --> 00:05:38,716
It's basically a manual on how to practice and all sorts of things.

50
00:05:39,216 --> 00:05:42,480
And it's considered to be a handbook on Theravada Buddhism.

51
00:05:42,781 --> 00:05:44,283
So whoever knows this book...

52
00:05:44,264 --> 00:05:47,189
Basically, it understood Theravada Buddhism.

53
00:05:48,130 --> 00:05:49,172
It's a pleasant weekend read.

54
00:05:52,699 --> 00:05:59,370
So, if we look at, first of all, the purification of virtue, this word sila,

55
00:05:59,771 --> 00:06:05,038
It's translated as morality, conduct, precepts, etc., etc.

56
00:06:05,939 --> 00:06:12,408
But the Buddha calls the actual precepts, for want of a better word, the Sikarpada.

57
00:06:12,668 --> 00:06:15,331
So it's the path, pada, of training.

58
00:06:15,432 --> 00:06:16,713
This is the path of training.

59
00:06:18,095 --> 00:06:24,783
And having established his four sanghas, laymen, laywomen, nuns, monks and that,

60
00:06:25,151 --> 00:06:31,439
he gave a basic sealer, a basic conduct concerning what not to do.

61
00:06:32,161 --> 00:06:33,483
So you all know them.

62
00:06:33,502 --> 00:06:35,425
It's the five precepts.

63
00:06:35,446 --> 00:06:42,915
And then if you want to strengthen it, you do the eight precepts, which these days is talked about as going for an agarica.

64
00:06:42,935 --> 00:06:45,598
So you've got a lay sort of junior monastic.

65
00:06:46,800 --> 00:06:50,444
Then you take the ten precepts, and at that point you would become an order member.

66
00:06:51,447 --> 00:06:52,408
And then you take

67
00:06:52,709 --> 00:06:57,915
this whole load of precepts, 227 of them, when you enter the order.

68
00:07:00,197 --> 00:07:05,083
All these precepts, as far as I know, are all negatives, what you don't do.

69
00:07:07,144 --> 00:07:17,315
And it's always starting from the position that our behavior, which is unskillful and unwholesome, is a measure of our delusion.

70
00:07:18,240 --> 00:07:28,470
So if we can stop that behavior, if we can actually put an end to that sort of behavior, then it draws us into the middle, away from it, when it begins to take off as a virtue.

71
00:07:29,713 --> 00:07:32,942
So if you look at something like the first precept, not to kill,

72
00:07:34,120 --> 00:07:43,872
not to kill human beings, that's the most grossest thing, you see, but then you can refine that to not to harm any living being, not to harm any living being.

73
00:07:43,891 --> 00:07:51,521
But of course, when you move to that position of not harming any living being, there's a movement towards compassion, isn't there?

74
00:07:51,541 --> 00:07:57,850
See, it's the opposite, towards amity, love and all that, it shades one into the other.

75
00:07:57,829 --> 00:08:04,920
If you think about the next one, which is not to take what is not freely given, so obviously a gross would be to rob a bank.

76
00:08:05,822 --> 00:08:14,557
In its more finer thing, it's actually not to take anything which has not been given to you at all, so even a pen from work.

77
00:08:15,418 --> 00:08:19,704
You can't take it because it's not been actually given to you for any other purpose than to be at work.

78
00:08:20,165 --> 00:08:21,487
It's a sort of refinement.

79
00:08:21,507 --> 00:08:25,473
The opposite, of course, what you move into is generosity, giving away.

80
00:08:25,959 --> 00:08:30,846
And then of course you find that by being generous, you lose your desire for things.

81
00:08:32,008 --> 00:08:37,333
Remember that stealing or taking something that's forbidden is just feeding that ego which feels this lack.

82
00:08:38,816 --> 00:08:48,187
So by giving something, you actually undo the process of that lack within you by an act of generosity.

83
00:08:49,619 --> 00:08:59,490
If you take that whole business around sexual behavior, I mean, as it's grossest, it's all sorts of horrible stuff, rape and all that.

84
00:08:59,570 --> 00:09:15,626
Then as you get more and more refined, you get to the point of, say, for instance, just sex for sex is safe, which Woody Allen pointed out was an empty experience, but as empty experiences go, it was not right.

85
00:09:15,606 --> 00:09:25,682
If it moves into a loving relationship, then of course it moves into something much more meaningful.

86
00:09:26,303 --> 00:09:40,647
But the end refinement of that, very difficult for people to come to accept, is of course celibacy, because it's drawing out the energy or the desire to find happiness in sexual pleasure.

87
00:09:41,128 --> 00:09:41,749
It draws out.

88
00:09:43,653 --> 00:09:50,061
If you take wrong speech, so obviously on one side it's just real whoppers, you know, greatly lies.

89
00:09:50,861 --> 00:10:07,280
And as you then stop exaggerating, to stop even an effort to exaggerate, to go beyond as far as you can see what the facts are, and then of course it becomes generous speech, truthful speech, kindly speech, because you're not trying to gain anything from it.

90
00:10:08,240 --> 00:10:15,836
When it comes to the alcohol and all that sort of stuff, and it's grossest, of course, getting blind drunk or on drugs.

91
00:10:16,693 --> 00:10:24,442
But as you become more and more refined, then you obviously feel that alcohol does have this effect on your consciousness, you see.

92
00:10:25,403 --> 00:10:34,594
And interestingly enough, in one of the recensions, one of the classifications of the morality, only the first four are rated.

93
00:10:35,215 --> 00:10:40,100
The last one's put in because it's under that influence that we actually do harm, you see.

94
00:10:41,001 --> 00:10:45,586
But of course, you can take drugs and drinks and stuff like that which can actually harm the body.

95
00:10:46,376 --> 00:10:50,647
So it's a refinement of that, you see, of caring for the body.

96
00:10:51,008 --> 00:10:56,741
So then one moves into being very careful what you feed the body, what you put into the body.

97
00:11:02,053 --> 00:11:11,177
So, on the one level, you have all these precepts, all worked out at these different levels, which are guiding us not to fall into error.

98
00:11:11,677 --> 00:11:18,595
And then you have, for instance, all the parami, the perfections, which are telling us what to develop on the other side.

99
00:11:18,575 --> 00:11:31,133
So the whole of our personality or psychology is being moved through the practice of these practices of sila, of conduct.

100
00:11:31,474 --> 00:11:41,148
We're moving from something which is quite gross and an expression of our delusion towards something which is an expression of the Enlightenment.

101
00:11:41,168 --> 00:11:47,417
So finally, you get to the Vinaya, the rule of the monks.

102
00:11:48,562 --> 00:11:50,467
So what's the Buddha actually trying to do there?

103
00:11:50,528 --> 00:11:52,855
Because it's all what you can't do.

104
00:11:52,875 --> 00:11:56,967
There's nothing in the Vinaya which says what you can do, it just says what you can't do.

105
00:11:57,421 --> 00:12:02,889
But interestingly enough, there's parts of the Vinaya which are to do with gross things, like not to steal, not to kill.

106
00:12:03,389 --> 00:12:06,594
But when you come to the end, it becomes very refined.

107
00:12:06,653 --> 00:12:10,139
Like, for instance, you're not supposed to chapu-chapu and suru-suru.

108
00:12:10,820 --> 00:12:16,027
Chapu-chapu means to chop your food, and suru-suru means to slurp your drink.

109
00:12:16,808 --> 00:12:19,451
We've got all these little rules, you see, and we're not supposed to talk.

110
00:12:19,511 --> 00:12:24,499
If I talk to my neighbour here, I should be in a voice which the other neighbour doesn't hear.

111
00:12:24,539 --> 00:12:24,879
Right?

112
00:12:25,432 --> 00:12:33,764
So there's a sort of effort to point out that as we become more and more refined, everything becomes more and more refined.

113
00:12:35,668 --> 00:12:45,642
The problem of course for the modern age is that many of these rules and regulations were to do with that particular society and time.

114
00:12:46,243 --> 00:12:53,533
But when it comes to the refinement, then it does actually pass through time.

115
00:12:56,179 --> 00:13:21,259
so now the big problem for people who are into developing that sort of purity the purity of sila, the purity of conduct is that they can get themselves into a double bind because the double bind is I cannot attain the enlightenment until the sila is perfected ok

116
00:13:22,268 --> 00:13:27,250
But I can't have perfect sila until I'm enlightened.

117
00:13:28,309 --> 00:13:30,072
It only comes with the Enlightenment.

118
00:13:30,611 --> 00:13:38,740
So you'll often get people in the monastic orders especially who get themselves in this ridiculous double bind and they just end up worrying all the time.

119
00:13:39,500 --> 00:13:40,041
Going to hell.

120
00:13:41,042 --> 00:13:46,866
So the point of the matter is that these are just sort of guidelines.

121
00:13:46,886 --> 00:13:51,611
They're given to us as guidelines as to what not to do and what to do.

122
00:13:51,851 --> 00:13:57,557
So even if you look at the discourses concerning people...

123
00:13:57,537 --> 00:14:04,832
Family life, you know, how the husband should treat the wife, the wife, the husband, and all that sort of stuff.

124
00:14:04,852 --> 00:14:14,774
Even though it's dated, you can see that there was a contractual way of dealing with family members, which was to produce peace, harmony, and goodwill.

125
00:14:16,519 --> 00:14:17,301
Okay.

126
00:14:17,904 --> 00:14:19,086
So that's the basis.

127
00:14:19,807 --> 00:14:24,774
Now when we go through these, it's not a case of that they come, first you do this, then you do that.

128
00:14:25,216 --> 00:14:26,618
It's a continual motion.

129
00:14:27,178 --> 00:14:28,280
It's a continual motion.

130
00:14:28,681 --> 00:14:38,777
So being aware of our ethical behavior, of our moral behavior, is the basic rule for spiritual advancement.

131
00:14:40,940 --> 00:14:43,744
Every time we behave unskillfully, it's a measure of our delusion.

132
00:14:46,001 --> 00:14:54,298
So you can't, you know, a lot of people might like to say, well, you know, I want to meditate, I want to get on with it, but I don't want to keep these rules.

133
00:14:54,557 --> 00:14:55,259
They get in the way.

134
00:14:56,000 --> 00:15:02,572
But in fact, you can't do that, because these rules that you break are measuring back to you your state of delusion.

135
00:15:04,836 --> 00:15:05,038
Okay.

136
00:15:05,057 --> 00:15:05,158
Okay.

137
00:15:08,716 --> 00:15:11,505
The next section is the purification of the mind.

138
00:15:11,525 --> 00:15:18,067
Now this actually refers to the development of the jhana, absorptions.

139
00:15:19,059 --> 00:15:28,715
So having now worked with trying to get rid of unskillful actions of speech and body, that's what sila is.

140
00:15:29,115 --> 00:15:30,376
It doesn't matter what's going on in your head.

141
00:15:30,437 --> 00:15:35,826
It's just that you don't throw it outward into the world in terms of something that you say or something that you do.

142
00:15:35,865 --> 00:15:40,613
You then work inwardly through concentration exercises.

143
00:15:41,302 --> 00:15:45,227
And concentration exercises can take you into these lovely jhanic states.

144
00:15:45,648 --> 00:15:53,399
And what the meditator knows by that is that in order to get these beautiful states, ecstatic states, they don't actually need the world out there.

145
00:15:54,902 --> 00:16:05,638
You can produce them within yourself just by repetition of a word or the use of an image or the use of an emotion like love, metta.

146
00:16:06,412 --> 00:16:19,993
And you can go through these little stages of bliss and reach these lovely states of inner happiness and they're not dependent on what you've eaten or who's been talking to you.

147
00:16:20,513 --> 00:16:27,423
And the danger, of course, is to find yourself in a little hut stuck somewhere up in a mountain and being absolutely blissed out.

148
00:16:27,961 --> 00:16:37,653
But remember that the problem with Samatha, the problem with that sort of meditation, is that it always sits upon those parts of us in our hearts which have not been dealt with.

149
00:16:39,777 --> 00:16:41,119
Now that can be extended.

150
00:16:41,458 --> 00:16:43,822
That can be extended to the abhinya, the powers.

151
00:16:44,663 --> 00:16:51,312
So you end up with things like the divine eye, the divine ear, which means that you can see through walls and hear things which other people can't hear.

152
00:16:51,692 --> 00:16:55,076
You can read people's minds and all those sorts of things.

153
00:16:55,418 --> 00:16:55,538
Right?

154
00:16:55,889 --> 00:17:00,745
And that's the development of the mind which goes beyond the frame, the physical frame.

155
00:17:01,808 --> 00:17:03,654
See, the physical frame.

156
00:17:04,292 --> 00:17:26,992
you can see how in the development of sila conduct it can shade off and from what is unwholesome to wholesomeness and you move into compassion so you can see the extension of sila the extension of the parami the extension of perfection is the bodhisattva ideal which is what the Mahayana did with it

157
00:17:27,563 --> 00:17:40,594
when it comes to the jhāna and the powers you can see the Tantra took that line and began to develop it and took the position that to be a fully fledged Buddha you had to be able to do this

158
00:17:41,721 --> 00:17:59,815
So now, having developed these different powers of honor, which is not necessary, remember that there are two paths, the dve jnana, in Theravada they use the word jnana, you know, somebody remind me, jnana, what does it mean?

159
00:17:59,795 --> 00:18:00,916
Vehicle, thank you.

160
00:18:02,278 --> 00:18:04,280
The dve jnana and the ekka jnana.

161
00:18:04,361 --> 00:18:09,567
So the dve jnana is to practice your concentration and your vipassana.

162
00:18:10,048 --> 00:18:12,531
One developing against the other.

163
00:18:13,374 --> 00:18:18,039
One of the great masters of that, if you read his books, is Ajahn Mahabua.

164
00:18:18,019 --> 00:18:20,604
He has it in his manual on how to practice.

165
00:18:20,624 --> 00:18:21,986
He practices the jhāna.

166
00:18:22,446 --> 00:18:23,728
He goes for a rest in jhāna.

167
00:18:23,748 --> 00:18:25,131
When he's ready, he goes back to vipassana.

168
00:18:25,330 --> 00:18:28,115
When he's had enough of that, he goes back to jhāna, refreshes himself.

169
00:18:28,474 --> 00:18:29,938
And in this way, you can sit for hours.

170
00:18:31,779 --> 00:18:45,039
But the ekayāna, the direct path, if you're a fundamentalist, the only path, according to Jnana Ponika, Bhikkhu Bodhi, those of you who know, corrected him and put the direct path here.

171
00:18:45,289 --> 00:18:49,255
Ekkayana means the one-way path, which is through just vipassana.

172
00:18:49,516 --> 00:18:51,357
And that's really the path of the Mahasi.

173
00:18:52,440 --> 00:19:01,311
The Mahasi system is just that one path, which is not at all concerned with trying to get blissed out or anything of that nature, but to develop vipassana to the bitter end.

174
00:19:02,492 --> 00:19:05,998
Okay, so that's your second purification.

175
00:19:09,876 --> 00:19:20,315
Now, at this point, we're ready to move, as it were, into the purifications of view, which is going to change our relationship to the world and bring about the libanic peace.

176
00:19:20,455 --> 00:19:30,432
And the first thing is the purification of view, meaning here wrong view about the personality, about the body.

177
00:19:30,598 --> 00:19:33,402
and you begin to separate the body from the mind.

178
00:19:34,883 --> 00:19:41,588
So the first thing that in your meditation you begin to do is recognize that this is the body and this is the mind.

179
00:19:42,088 --> 00:19:45,332
So for instance, the rising and falling of the abdomen is the body.

180
00:19:45,833 --> 00:19:48,855
That which knows it, notes it, is the mind.

181
00:19:49,135 --> 00:19:50,217
They're two different things.

182
00:19:51,498 --> 00:19:53,179
You begin to separate these things out.

183
00:19:53,619 --> 00:19:58,564
When you're eating, you note that the sensation on your tongue is the body

184
00:19:58,544 --> 00:20:01,394
The heart with its response of joy is the mind.

185
00:20:02,979 --> 00:20:09,381
This is beginning to, as it were, undo this wholesomeness, this whole, the idea that things are whole.

186
00:20:09,782 --> 00:20:16,032
If you look at the canon, the Buddha's constantly trying to deconstruct what we think to be entire.

187
00:20:16,513 --> 00:20:20,339
He does it by way of the five khandhas, the five heaps.

188
00:20:20,559 --> 00:20:27,892
He does it by way of the six ayatanas, the six spheres, referring to the six senses.

189
00:20:28,353 --> 00:20:30,355
He does it by way of the dhatus, right?

190
00:20:30,476 --> 00:20:35,284
So he's constantly saying to us, look, if you look, you'll see everything's compounded.

191
00:20:36,022 --> 00:20:44,079
But that looking has to be within ourselves through this careful investigation, this careful watching of what's happening inside us.

192
00:20:45,763 --> 00:20:49,712
So that's actually a vipassana knowledge.

193
00:20:49,732 --> 00:20:53,621
And that has to be more and more clarified as we meditate.

194
00:20:53,641 --> 00:20:56,326
And that changes our relationship.

195
00:20:57,184 --> 00:21:17,961
to the body and mind the next one is the condition it's called the purification of overcoming doubt and what it's referring to is the karma it's referring to how things are happening and especially the role of intention so

196
00:21:18,936 --> 00:21:27,931
When I watch the abdomen rising and falling and I note rising and falling, this noting is dependent on the rising and falling of the abdomen.

197
00:21:28,090 --> 00:21:33,459
It's very simple stuff, but it's just catching the fact that everything arises dependent on everything else.

198
00:21:34,621 --> 00:21:36,202
So nothing has its own existence.

199
00:21:37,599 --> 00:21:43,204
So that knowledge can be taken to its ultimate degree of full enlightenment.

200
00:21:43,565 --> 00:21:48,269
But at this stage, it's just beginning to recognize this business of dependency.

201
00:21:48,849 --> 00:21:54,335
So when we do our walking meditation, we say intending to walk.

202
00:21:54,375 --> 00:21:57,478
We actually acknowledge that without the intention, you don't walk.

203
00:21:58,638 --> 00:22:00,080
One is the mind, one is the body.

204
00:22:01,922 --> 00:22:05,885
So they're all rising in this codependent way.

205
00:22:08,464 --> 00:22:12,634
So by now the meditator is actually meditating.

206
00:22:13,655 --> 00:22:20,470
From now on we're talking about insights, vipassana insights, to see things as they really are.

207
00:22:21,372 --> 00:22:25,359
So the first one to do with conduct was basically how we live our lives.

208
00:22:25,828 --> 00:22:34,166
The next one, which is not absolutely necessary for enlightenment, is how we develop the beautiful factors within our minds.

209
00:22:35,288 --> 00:22:45,069
And then we begin to do this careful investigation, careful direct experience of the body and mind, and these are the sorts of insights we come up with.

210
00:22:46,618 --> 00:23:00,480
Then we finally begin to really meditate and we begin to see the three characteristics, one of them or all of them, one after the other, it doesn't matter, you're just aware of one of the three characteristics.

211
00:23:01,121 --> 00:23:03,565
So now this is mainly happening within your meditations.

212
00:23:04,134 --> 00:23:18,651
As you begin to develop this, the concentration is growing and you're really able to contact the fact that within your view you really see things that are arising and passing away.

213
00:23:19,255 --> 00:23:25,800
And such is the force of your concentration that it's actually the same as first jhana.

214
00:23:26,682 --> 00:23:30,465
And at that point, the mind is still.

215
00:23:30,906 --> 00:23:32,008
There's still thinking.

216
00:23:32,667 --> 00:23:44,519
The first jhana, you can have some thinking around it, some ideas come up, but the attention of the meditator is always on the experience, on the sensations as they arise and pass away.

217
00:23:44,500 --> 00:23:50,205
Remember that although I'm talking about the breath, it's anything which arises within the mind.

218
00:23:51,247 --> 00:23:53,609
An emotion, a feeling, a thought.

219
00:23:54,411 --> 00:23:56,532
It's just seen as arising and passing away.

220
00:23:57,634 --> 00:24:03,180
Or how we create suffering by forming a relationship of wanting and not wanting.

221
00:24:03,941 --> 00:24:07,164
Or we get this idea that it's not me, not mine, because we're looking at it.

222
00:24:08,346 --> 00:24:08,465
Right?

223
00:24:13,103 --> 00:24:18,477
Just to point that out, in the commentaries they make the distinction between these two jhanas.

224
00:24:18,958 --> 00:24:22,105
One is called Lākana jhāna and the other one is called Aramana jhāna.

225
00:24:22,487 --> 00:24:25,694
The Lākana jhāna is that concentration

226
00:24:26,114 --> 00:24:32,226
which is achieved on a characteristic, a micha dukanata.

227
00:24:33,509 --> 00:24:34,451
That's the concentration.

228
00:24:34,691 --> 00:24:44,832
That's why it's known as kanika samadhi, momentary samadhi, meaning that it doesn't matter what arises and passes away within your consciousness, you're there with it.

229
00:24:46,297 --> 00:24:52,567
The Aramana jhana is the concentration you get on an object, on a still object.

230
00:24:52,728 --> 00:24:56,753
And that's why in jhana practice you always give the mind one object.

231
00:24:56,874 --> 00:25:00,000
It could be just a feeling like may all beings be happy.

232
00:25:00,539 --> 00:25:04,165
Or it could be one of these circles that you look at and then internalize.

233
00:25:04,267 --> 00:25:08,153
It doesn't matter, it needs one object and the concentration grows around it.

234
00:25:09,500 --> 00:25:10,781
Okay?

235
00:25:10,801 --> 00:25:18,309
So, this idea of kanika samadhi, moment-to-moment concentration, is to do with the vipassana mind.

236
00:25:19,372 --> 00:25:26,339
And the distinction between the vipassana mind and the samatha mind is that in the vipassana mind, there's intelligence.

237
00:25:28,182 --> 00:25:31,685
You're actually making, there's a curiosity there, a wanting to know.

238
00:25:31,705 --> 00:25:36,592
Okay?

239
00:25:36,612 --> 00:25:37,633
Then,

240
00:25:39,976 --> 00:25:49,448
Once that becomes clear, what happens is that delights arise which always come with good concentration.

241
00:25:50,568 --> 00:25:55,295
And one begins to get what's known as the vipassana kilesa, the defilements of vipassana.

242
00:25:56,175 --> 00:26:01,241
And there's about ten of them, just to give you some idea.

243
00:26:05,541 --> 00:26:07,044
A light can appear in the mind.

244
00:26:07,064 --> 00:26:08,726
A bright light.

245
00:26:08,786 --> 00:26:12,230
Your head just brightens up.

246
00:26:12,250 --> 00:26:12,652
Inside.

247
00:26:14,374 --> 00:26:15,576
People might think they're enlightened.

248
00:26:19,040 --> 00:26:20,742
Rapture, pity, great joy.

249
00:26:20,762 --> 00:26:22,285
Happiness.

250
00:26:23,006 --> 00:26:24,868
An enormous amount of energy arises.

251
00:26:24,888 --> 00:26:26,790
You can meditate hours on end.

252
00:26:26,810 --> 00:26:27,771
You don't have to go to sleep.

253
00:26:29,914 --> 00:26:30,596
Equanimity.

254
00:26:31,637 --> 00:26:32,459
You think you know it.

255
00:26:32,479 --> 00:26:33,519
You think you've understood it.

256
00:26:33,539 --> 00:26:34,721
You're about to write a book.

257
00:26:36,827 --> 00:26:37,788
People get very deluded.

258
00:26:38,971 --> 00:26:39,711
Tranquility.

259
00:26:39,751 --> 00:26:41,755
Peace, lovely peace.

260
00:26:42,276 --> 00:26:45,359
Determination, this enormous determination to get on with the job.

261
00:26:45,901 --> 00:26:47,022
Enormous devotion.

262
00:26:50,167 --> 00:26:53,531
All of these are actually healthy things.

263
00:26:53,551 --> 00:26:54,574
They're all skillful.

264
00:26:54,634 --> 00:26:57,778
What makes them unskillful is the last one, nikanti.

265
00:26:58,239 --> 00:27:00,102
And nikanti is that indulgence.

266
00:27:01,432 --> 00:27:13,609
And that's the mistake people make, because especially if they've never touched this sort of stuff before, and they experience these ecstatic states, they often mistake it for some real insight experience.

267
00:27:15,712 --> 00:27:26,307
I know a friend of mine, he always talks about this, he was hardly at Amarwati, and he was actually on the toilet.

268
00:27:29,089 --> 00:27:30,915
And this beautiful feeling came up.

269
00:27:31,217 --> 00:27:32,701
And he was certain that he was enlightened.

270
00:27:33,083 --> 00:27:40,990
Luther got his insight while he was on the toilet.

271
00:27:44,732 --> 00:28:06,268
So, nisipasana kilesa, when the joy comes up, then you note them, exactly the same technique, you see what they are, etc., and you keep putting your attention, your curiosity, on the three characteristics, especially the rising and falling, especially anicca, everything's arising and passing away.

272
00:28:06,248 --> 00:28:12,095
Then you hit what you might call the real insight, or something which shakes the mind.

273
00:28:12,275 --> 00:28:16,299
And that is suddenly, there is this realization that everything comes to an end.

274
00:28:16,901 --> 00:28:18,742
Banga Jnana.

275
00:28:18,883 --> 00:28:20,924
And by that time, you're actually in the fourth jhana.

276
00:28:21,246 --> 00:28:23,848
Your actual concentration has to be that sharp.

277
00:28:25,049 --> 00:28:27,232
And that knowledge there is a cutting point.

278
00:28:27,874 --> 00:28:29,095
Because now that's death.

279
00:28:29,935 --> 00:28:34,922
It reverberates back on the mind, and your whole meditation collapses into what's known as the Dukkha Jnanas.

280
00:28:36,032 --> 00:28:39,298
Now the Dukkha Jnana starts off first of all with a shaking of fear.

281
00:28:40,160 --> 00:28:41,342
It's only a momentary thing.

282
00:28:42,063 --> 00:28:47,872
But then there arises this feeling of disgust, a sort of horror to what's actually happening.

283
00:28:48,353 --> 00:28:50,276
And eventually shades into a weariness.

284
00:28:50,355 --> 00:28:56,926
And it's at this level that meditators suffer from enormous sloth, enormous talk or anger, all that sort of stuff.

285
00:28:58,595 --> 00:29:02,923
Then as they go on, and they just keep meditating, you can get locked in these things, you see.

286
00:29:03,786 --> 00:29:06,652
And remember that these things are also feeding into your psychology.

287
00:29:07,313 --> 00:29:15,490
So part of it will be the spiritual insight of death, of the loss of self, and part of it will be because there's a load of sloth down there.

288
00:29:15,976 --> 00:29:18,861
And it's bringing it up through this avenue.

289
00:29:19,563 --> 00:29:22,528
And you keep going, you keep going, you just keep going.

290
00:29:22,749 --> 00:29:30,001
And sloth and torpor are authentic, valid, perfectly wonderful states of mind to be observed and get curious about.

291
00:29:30,606 --> 00:29:35,233
And then it shades into a desire to escape.

292
00:29:35,413 --> 00:29:37,998
And that's this great restlessness that comes upon the meditator.

293
00:29:38,377 --> 00:29:40,240
Often they start packing their bags and all that.

294
00:29:41,021 --> 00:29:47,090
There was a lovely Carthusian monk who had meditated in Rangoon at the Mahasi Centre.

295
00:29:47,711 --> 00:29:49,894
And he was very impressed by this.

296
00:29:50,215 --> 00:29:55,683
He got his bags packed and he went to the teacher and he said, you know, he just couldn't handle it.

297
00:29:55,703 --> 00:29:58,407
He just couldn't meditate, his mind was all over the place, absolutely a waste of time.

298
00:29:58,468 --> 00:29:59,769
And the teacher said...

299
00:29:59,750 --> 00:30:01,491
He'll have made it in 21 days.

300
00:30:02,512 --> 00:30:05,557
On the 21st day, he made Sada Grana.

301
00:30:07,259 --> 00:30:14,508
And just to finish that story off, he turned up a couple of months, a couple of years later to continue his training, and they said to him, you're a Buddhist now.

302
00:30:15,068 --> 00:30:15,648
And he said, no.

303
00:30:15,910 --> 00:30:17,551
And they were utterly confused by that.

304
00:30:19,954 --> 00:30:23,298
And the fact is that these insights are not culture bound.

305
00:30:23,338 --> 00:30:24,519
They're not even religion bound.

306
00:30:25,560 --> 00:30:28,525
So that he would take that insight back into Christianity.

307
00:30:28,605 --> 00:30:30,651
And re-translated in a Christian way.

308
00:30:30,951 --> 00:30:33,116
And that's what he was doing, actually.

309
00:30:33,136 --> 00:30:34,319
He was getting in trouble with his cardinal.

310
00:30:37,528 --> 00:30:39,051
He died, unfortunately.

311
00:30:39,071 --> 00:30:39,553
A lovely man.

312
00:30:40,474 --> 00:30:43,762
So then, once we've got to that...

313
00:30:45,498 --> 00:30:49,825
These contemplations of weariness and the desire for deliverance, they're all about special names.

314
00:30:50,707 --> 00:30:53,191
There comes finally this reflection knowledge.

315
00:30:53,371 --> 00:31:01,785
And at this point, this intelligence, this panna, centers on a particular characteristic, and it is seen at a depth not seen before.

316
00:31:01,765 --> 00:31:05,330
And now this is used as the gateway to nirvana.

317
00:31:05,592 --> 00:31:09,499
So if it sees anicca clearly, that's what it'll use to become enlightened.

318
00:31:09,578 --> 00:31:11,923
If it sees dukkha, it'll use that if it sees anatta.

319
00:31:12,463 --> 00:31:15,769
Now it's absolutely locked into that meditation.

320
00:31:16,151 --> 00:31:18,674
And it moves into what's known as sankhara upeka.

321
00:31:19,016 --> 00:31:24,786
Sankhara upeka is a state when the meditator simply cannot lose their awareness.

322
00:31:24,766 --> 00:31:25,708
It just stays.

323
00:31:25,788 --> 00:31:28,092
It is just so developed and so locked.

324
00:31:29,315 --> 00:31:33,803
And there's an undeveloped part and a developed part.

325
00:31:34,124 --> 00:31:36,990
In the undeveloped part, there's still some shaking.

326
00:31:37,269 --> 00:31:44,022
And it's at this point that some trauma, some fundamental disturbance in the psyche is liberated.

327
00:31:45,167 --> 00:31:58,299
To give you a sort of example of that, the very famous monk from Sri Lanka, a very old fellow, he died recently at the age of 101, somebody must know him.

328
00:31:59,224 --> 00:32:28,236
Maitreya Ananda Maitreya so he came to Khandavoda which is my own monastery to practice in the Mahasi tradition and he came to this point and he suddenly had a memory of taking the Bodhisattva vow at the Buddha's time he remembered Sariputta's face and Moggallana's face but he couldn't remember the Buddha and he made this vow to become a Buddha so there's no way he could progress

329
00:32:30,038 --> 00:32:31,119
Bodhisattva.

330
00:32:31,180 --> 00:32:32,622
No, a self-enlightened Buddha.

331
00:32:32,803 --> 00:32:33,344
That's what it means.

332
00:32:33,403 --> 00:32:41,557
In Theravada, if you take the Bodhisattva vow, it means you vow to become a self-enlightened Buddha, which is different from the Mahayana.

333
00:32:42,558 --> 00:32:47,186
So he had taken the vow to become a self-enlightened Buddha.

334
00:32:47,166 --> 00:32:49,170
So from that point on, he couldn't move.

335
00:32:49,711 --> 00:32:53,957
The rest of his life was developing his parami, he was developing his abilities.

336
00:32:55,420 --> 00:33:11,284
And in the mythology, he will keep doing that until all the paramis are ready, he will be reborn into a particular place, a particular time, and within that life, go through the four stages of sanctity.

337
00:33:13,053 --> 00:33:17,638
So that's the state of your sankara upeka, right?

338
00:33:18,138 --> 00:33:26,209
And then the mind is on, and then it's put in this sort of way, there's a change of lineage, meaning that there's a shift in the level of consciousness.

339
00:33:26,568 --> 00:33:27,590
Now what do we mean by that?

340
00:33:28,050 --> 00:33:31,996
The best example that we've all been through is between the ages of six and eight.

341
00:33:33,136 --> 00:33:37,082
Between six and eight, two things, many things happen, but two things in particular.

342
00:33:37,542 --> 00:33:39,464
The first is a reality test.

343
00:33:40,171 --> 00:33:42,942
At the age of six, Father Christmas can come down the chimney.

344
00:33:43,826 --> 00:33:44,730
It's not a problem, is it?

345
00:33:45,894 --> 00:33:47,480
At the age of eight, it's ridiculous.

346
00:33:48,877 --> 00:34:17,990
so at the age of 6 what I imagine is just as real as what I experience out there at the age of 8 the distinction is made and you can't go back on that relationship to the world anymore the second thing that happens is even though young children do feel shame do feel guilt and all that at the age of 7 it becomes something concretised it becomes an actual complex within the mind about what's bad and what's good and again you cannot go back

347
00:34:18,393 --> 00:34:18,934
You've shifted.

348
00:34:19,735 --> 00:34:23,440
So at this point there's a shift in consciousness.

349
00:34:24,483 --> 00:34:28,409
And then it takes its object as one of these characteristics.

350
00:34:29,952 --> 00:34:36,503
And it sees it at such a deep level that that shift in the level of consciousness has been changed for good.

351
00:34:36,563 --> 00:34:36,884
That's it.

352
00:34:37,425 --> 00:34:39,208
And that's why it's called stream entrant.

353
00:34:39,929 --> 00:34:41,831
You're entering into the stream of nobility.

354
00:34:42,554 --> 00:34:43,454
The Sotapanna.

355
00:34:44,481 --> 00:34:49,331
And at that point, after that, there is a momentary experience of nirvana.

356
00:34:49,632 --> 00:34:51,235
And then there's a coming back.

357
00:34:51,255 --> 00:34:59,871
The experience of that changes the view that this body, mind and heart, this personality, is the self.

358
00:35:00,673 --> 00:35:02,456
But it only changes the view.

359
00:35:02,824 --> 00:35:16,885
it doesn't change the relationship so the Sotapanna still acts and still believes at a certain level that they are the body the mind and the heart but they've seen it and the Buddha talks of it like a flash of lightning hmm

360
00:35:17,253 --> 00:35:21,382
Now, to get to the next stage, it's the very same process.

361
00:35:21,402 --> 00:35:22,887
It just deepens, it just deepens.

362
00:35:23,447 --> 00:35:26,896
Some people, it's said, get there just by seeing transience all the way.

363
00:35:27,478 --> 00:35:30,826
Some people by just seeing suffering, some people by just seeing not-self.

364
00:35:31,367 --> 00:35:35,076
Others by seeing the three, quite separately in each stage.

365
00:35:36,288 --> 00:35:44,096
So the other fetter that goes when you enter the stream is, of course, you lose doubt, because now you've seen the top of the mountain.

366
00:35:44,215 --> 00:35:45,458
There's not a problem anymore.

367
00:35:45,478 --> 00:35:48,019
So there's no doubt within the Sotapanna.

368
00:35:48,740 --> 00:35:53,266
In terms of the Buddhist society, in terms of the Buddhist community, this is enormously important.

369
00:35:54,347 --> 00:36:02,295
It is said that if there comes a time when there is not a Sotapanna within the Buddhist community, the religion will shade away into useless rituals.

370
00:36:02,646 --> 00:36:08,407
and all this other stuff, because that vision has been lost in a community level, at a community level.

371
00:36:09,992 --> 00:36:10,193
See?

372
00:36:16,146 --> 00:36:25,221
So one goes through the same process, and what is undermined this time is your dependency on the world for happiness.

373
00:36:25,922 --> 00:36:27,443
It's undermined, it's not got rid of.

374
00:36:27,905 --> 00:36:31,369
And your anger, your aversion is undermined.

375
00:36:31,771 --> 00:36:35,016
The Buddha talks about it, seeing things in a full starlit night.

376
00:36:36,650 --> 00:36:43,519
The third one, the anagami, the non-returner, he says it's like seeing things as they really are in the full moon.

377
00:36:43,541 --> 00:36:46,373
In the topical full moon you can see colour.

378
00:36:47,516 --> 00:36:53,407
And it's only when we become fully enlightened that you can see things like the midday sun.

379
00:36:53,427 --> 00:36:54,728
But the process is the same.

380
00:36:55,128 --> 00:37:07,989
This continuous effort to see these three characteristics and just the deepening of that effort until consciousness is utterly liberated from trying to seek happiness in the phenomenal world.

381
00:37:09,690 --> 00:37:13,717
So there's a whole total new relationship going on to the whole process.

382
00:37:14,777 --> 00:37:20,525
And as that process goes, everything is being refined and being extended and being developed.

383
00:37:21,047 --> 00:37:23,210
And it's up to the person to develop what they want.

384
00:37:24,231 --> 00:37:32,242
So it may be that all our behavior is becoming more and more refined, more and more gentle, etc.

385
00:37:32,541 --> 00:37:35,867
And we decide to develop compassion.

386
00:37:36,016 --> 00:37:39,481
It may be that instead you decide to develop your intellect.

387
00:37:40,161 --> 00:37:42,304
It may be that you decide to develop your powers.

388
00:37:42,865 --> 00:37:47,632
So when Moggallana asks Sariputta, how is it he's not developed the powers?

389
00:37:47,813 --> 00:37:50,396
He has this enormous understanding, second only to the Buddha.

390
00:37:50,958 --> 00:37:52,981
Why hasn't he developed the powers like Moggallana?

391
00:37:53,541 --> 00:37:54,463
He says, I'm not interested.

392
00:37:56,806 --> 00:37:59,650
So even enlightened beings can be quite different.

393
00:38:00,050 --> 00:38:04,538
They don't turn out to be clones of

394
00:38:08,550 --> 00:38:18,001
And just to give you another image that the Buddha gives in terms of the path, he talks about people swimming underwater.

395
00:38:18,782 --> 00:38:21,324
They're the deluded ones.

396
00:38:21,344 --> 00:38:24,728
And he talks about people swimming and their heads bob up every so often.

397
00:38:24,748 --> 00:38:26,931
So they're the trainees.

398
00:38:27,813 --> 00:38:31,416
And then there's the ones who tread water.

399
00:38:31,436 --> 00:38:32,757
Their heads always bob up.

400
00:38:33,599 --> 00:38:36,161
Then there's the ones who swim towards the shore.

401
00:38:36,563 --> 00:38:42,612
They're the anaganis, they're the once-returner.

402
00:38:43,614 --> 00:38:47,800
And when you stand on the shore, you're finally on the island, then you're a non-returner.

403
00:38:48,382 --> 00:38:51,987
You've left at least this gross, sensual world.

404
00:38:52,007 --> 00:38:56,514
And you make your way to the centre of the island, and then you become a fully-fledged arahant.

405
00:38:58,117 --> 00:39:00,782
These images are very telling of the practice.

406
00:39:02,230 --> 00:39:07,217
The effort to get from underwater to be treading water is enormous.

407
00:39:09,681 --> 00:39:11,244
But once you get there, you can tread water.

408
00:39:11,623 --> 00:39:13,007
You can stay there for a very long time.

409
00:39:13,407 --> 00:39:17,273
The effort to get from treading water to the island is a real effort.

410
00:39:17,934 --> 00:39:21,780
Once you're on the island, it's no big deal getting to become enlightened.

411
00:39:23,161 --> 00:39:27,228
They're actually very valid sort of images that he uses.

412
00:39:27,648 --> 00:39:30,313
He's not just giving us little images for the sake of it.

413
00:39:34,427 --> 00:39:57,650
So, just finally, to link it in with the three characteristics that we've been discussing, it says, you see, whosoever being filled with determination, right, through the practice, considers all formations as impermanent, such a one attains the conditionless liberation.

414
00:39:58,552 --> 00:40:01,735
So they experience the liberation as being unconditioned.

415
00:40:03,858 --> 00:40:14,112
Whosoever being filled with tranquility considers the formations as unsatisfactory, dukkha, such a one attains the desireless liberation.

416
00:40:14,833 --> 00:40:19,300
For them, that experience of liberation is no desire, no attachment.

417
00:40:21,603 --> 00:40:31,637
Whosoever being filled with intuitive intelligence considers all formations as not-self, such a one attains the emptiness liberation, the sunyata.

418
00:40:32,478 --> 00:40:39,490
They experience it as empty of self.

419
00:40:39,510 --> 00:40:44,820
So, I think that brings me to an end of my explication.

420
00:40:45,422 --> 00:40:49,389
So, just to recap for you, these seven chariots

421
00:40:49,623 --> 00:40:55,894
were a concoction of Punya Mantani Buddha, his monk.

422
00:40:56,956 --> 00:40:58,900
And the Buddha said it was okay, it'll do.

423
00:40:59,481 --> 00:41:04,429
It was picked up by Upatissa, who is considered to be an Arahant, who is considered to be enlightened.

424
00:41:04,510 --> 00:41:07,315
It's a very different book from Buddhaghosa's.

425
00:41:07,335 --> 00:41:12,846
And Buddhaghosa took the same form to write his manual that we can read.

426
00:41:14,885 --> 00:41:16,606
And this is a very scholastic effort.

427
00:41:17,228 --> 00:41:19,490
You don't get the feeling that Buddha Gosu is an arahat.

428
00:41:19,610 --> 00:41:20,813
You get the feeling he's very clever.

429
00:41:20,833 --> 00:41:38,918
And then these seven factors are the purification of view, sorry, the purification of conduct, the purification of conduct by way of not doing what is skillful and developing what is skillful,

430
00:41:39,539 --> 00:41:48,398
The purification of the mind, meaning through the jhana, to build up those beautiful states, which remember is not necessary for the enlightenment.

431
00:41:48,900 --> 00:41:50,764
And then we begin the insight knowledges.

432
00:41:51,385 --> 00:41:55,353
The separation of body from mind, their connection,

433
00:41:55,942 --> 00:42:07,215
And then you go through the real vipassana jhanas, which is to see the three characteristics, to see dissolution, and then to go through the suffering of what is actually the suffering of death, the loss of self.

434
00:42:08,315 --> 00:42:10,838
The depression and all that sort of stuff, the running away.

435
00:42:11,300 --> 00:42:25,476
Suddenly there's an insight which directs you towards the goal, the equanimity, and then the reaching of the goal, the release of that consciousness from its fetters, which has been causing it trouble, and...

436
00:42:25,860 --> 00:42:35,318
an establishment of a certain level of consciousness, which is a way of relating to the world, not to be confused with a state of mind, which is an emotion or a thought.

437
00:42:36,400 --> 00:42:43,532
It's the way we relate to the world, the way we are in the world, which is what is changing through the practice of Vipassana.

438
00:42:54,682 --> 00:43:03,096
So, if you really want to know about that, in much more detail, I've written, I've given you some books.

439
00:43:04,257 --> 00:43:10,226
I think the ones that I'd like you to add on is The Heart of Buddhist Meditation by Jnana Ponica.

440
00:43:10,427 --> 00:43:13,072
It's still, I think it's still the classic.

441
00:43:13,952 --> 00:43:16,456
The Heart of Buddhist Meditation.

442
00:43:16,476 --> 00:43:19,661
The Handbook on Mental Training Based on the Buddha's Way of Mindfulness.

443
00:43:21,447 --> 00:43:24,431
A Heart of Buddhist Meditation by Jnana Ponika.

444
00:43:27,797 --> 00:43:32,284
N-Y-A-N-A-P-O-N-I-K-A.

445
00:43:33,487 --> 00:43:35,610
Jnana Ponika.

446
00:43:35,630 --> 00:43:43,943
N-Y-A-N-A-P-O-N-I-K-A.

447
00:43:45,606 --> 00:43:46,407
Jnana Ponika.

448
00:43:46,809 --> 00:43:56,909
And another minor classic, absolutely wonderful little book, Insight Meditation by Joseph Goldstein.

449
00:43:57,431 --> 00:44:02,099
These are just little essays, and it is based on the Mahasi technique, but it's a lovely little book.

450
00:44:02,561 --> 00:44:06,969
And it's something you can use on a personal retreat and just read occasional chapter.

451
00:44:08,351 --> 00:44:08,952
It's a lovely little book.

452
00:44:13,320 --> 00:44:30,215
the one for the stages of insight are the ones I've given you there on that piece of paper by Nyanarama the seven stages yeah also the Mahasi has written one called progress and insight I've written that down for you

453
00:44:31,563 --> 00:44:33,684
He's got his practical vipassana exercises.

454
00:44:34,485 --> 00:44:44,615
The seven contemplations of insight are just a greater explication of the three characteristics.

455
00:44:46,036 --> 00:44:49,581
This is definitely a classic in this very life by Upandita.

456
00:44:49,780 --> 00:44:53,344
And that's where he explains these vipassana jhanas which confuse so many people.

457
00:44:58,929 --> 00:45:00,911
That'll keep you going.

458
00:45:02,494 --> 00:45:05,639
Really, and the last is a caveat, is a warning.

459
00:45:07,481 --> 00:45:16,894
This is, I think, to my knowledge, I think I've done it twice before actually, this is the only time that I've actually taught this stuff.

460
00:45:16,914 --> 00:45:18,096
And the reason is very simple.

461
00:45:19,777 --> 00:45:26,367
It's so easy to get a conceptual idea of what the path is, and then you start striving for it.

462
00:45:26,867 --> 00:45:31,994
And you really, really have to tell yourself that this is completely beyond your control.

463
00:45:32,887 --> 00:45:33,568
Completely.

464
00:45:34,168 --> 00:45:37,733
You cannot make any of these insights happen.

465
00:45:37,753 --> 00:45:40,759
And if you try, then that's the ego getting in the way.

466
00:45:41,679 --> 00:45:41,920
You see?

467
00:45:42,380 --> 00:45:43,342
That's the ego getting in the way.

468
00:45:43,362 --> 00:45:50,572
So my advice to you is to sort of read them and just, as it were, know they're there because they're part of faith.

469
00:45:50,793 --> 00:45:52,996
I mean, this is a well-worn path.

470
00:45:53,577 --> 00:45:54,619
People experience it.

471
00:45:55,119 --> 00:45:56,121
It's there to be had.

472
00:45:56,681 --> 00:45:57,443
And then just to forget them.

473
00:46:02,148 --> 00:46:05,753
It's about the faith.

474
00:46:06,255 --> 00:46:10,101
Well, it's to point out, you see, people don't realize how delineated the path is.

475
00:46:10,121 --> 00:46:11,543
They think it's some sort of hazy thing.

476
00:46:12,385 --> 00:46:14,248
But it's very clearly delineated.

477
00:46:14,768 --> 00:46:17,072
And by the way, this isn't the only way you can become enlightened.

478
00:46:17,793 --> 00:46:21,239
This is the Theravada way through the practice of Vipassana.

479
00:46:25,445 --> 00:46:26,788
It's very, you know...

480
00:46:27,291 --> 00:46:28,193
It's possible.

481
00:46:29,775 --> 00:46:30,596
Forget time.

482
00:46:31,177 --> 00:46:32,978
I've known people to struggle for five years.

483
00:46:33,259 --> 00:46:34,820
I've known people to do it in six weeks.

484
00:46:36,143 --> 00:46:37,324
I've known people still at it.

485
00:46:38,644 --> 00:46:40,427
So forget time.

486
00:46:40,547 --> 00:46:41,768
It doesn't work like that.

487
00:46:42,150 --> 00:46:42,951
It doesn't work at all.

488
00:46:44,452 --> 00:46:50,719
But knowing this and within that sort of system, then you know, you just keep working and things arise.

489
00:46:52,581 --> 00:46:54,244
In this life or the next or the next.

490
00:46:56,603 --> 00:46:58,585
So I think that's my little bit.

491
00:46:59,485 --> 00:47:00,467
Really, it's just questions.

492
00:47:04,731 --> 00:47:21,327
Yeah.

493
00:47:32,311 --> 00:47:55,443
Well, I think that what he was establishing through the monastic path was a way, was an institution for that sort of commitment.

494
00:47:57,226 --> 00:48:02,233
If you really wanted to become enlightened, if you really did, you'd drop everything right now.

495
00:48:03,175 --> 00:48:25,335
well in any in any any path you want to choose if you really want it you'll go for it

496
00:48:25,534 --> 00:48:34,286
Can't you become enlightened without one of those paths?

497
00:48:34,746 --> 00:48:38,692
I don't know of any process of enlightenment which doesn't have a path to it, because it's a progress.

498
00:48:42,137 --> 00:48:44,400
It's not as though you're an enlightenment and suddenly you're enlightened.

499
00:48:45,621 --> 00:48:47,403
It's a development, there's a progress to it.

500
00:48:47,744 --> 00:48:50,648
Yeah, I just meant without...

501
00:48:56,449 --> 00:49:09,722
I think it's a very valid question.

502
00:49:10,001 --> 00:49:13,184
Say somebody just living on their own in the middle of nature.

503
00:49:13,204 --> 00:49:13,764
This is just an example.

504
00:49:13,784 --> 00:49:14,585
It could be anything.

505
00:49:14,766 --> 00:49:16,547
Living on their own in the middle of nature.

506
00:49:16,588 --> 00:49:19,329
Just living their life.

507
00:49:19,349 --> 00:49:24,954
I mean, without a program like you've set out like that, could they not in their own way

508
00:49:25,423 --> 00:49:28,849
achieve some degree of whatever it might be like?

509
00:49:28,869 --> 00:49:32,673
I don't know.

510
00:49:32,954 --> 00:49:35,396
I wouldn't do it.

511
00:49:35,416 --> 00:49:38,320
I don't sense that the woman is held back by the wife.

512
00:49:38,541 --> 00:49:40,063
I mean, I don't know.

513
00:49:40,083 --> 00:49:41,144
Just being honest, I felt.

514
00:49:42,586 --> 00:49:43,807
It can be a little dull.

515
00:49:43,847 --> 00:49:46,972
I didn't do it when I was there.

516
00:49:46,992 --> 00:49:50,436
But just the thought came up to me, Christianity.

517
00:49:51,157 --> 00:49:54,822
And I mean, his approach and his teaching seems to be

518
00:49:55,512 --> 00:50:02,201
very much about not following a path.

519
00:50:02,221 --> 00:50:03,382
Well, two things there.

520
00:50:03,422 --> 00:50:05,465
You're presuming he was enlightened.

521
00:50:05,485 --> 00:50:06,086
That's number one.

522
00:50:06,586 --> 00:50:14,157
And number two, even though he said meditation was useless and shouldn't follow a path, if you read his writings, it's full of a path.

523
00:50:14,217 --> 00:50:23,510
If there's a book on elements, element publication, by somebody who's written a book on Krishnamurti's teaching, it's definitely a path.

524
00:50:24,318 --> 00:50:35,875
I think there's a lot of contradictions there, but I think that's probably part of growing up into a way to investigate all of this in the West.

525
00:50:36,014 --> 00:50:45,809
I think that's part of it, but he seemed to offer, or suggested, whether he was enlightened or not.

526
00:50:45,829 --> 00:50:46,309
I think...

527
00:50:46,329 --> 00:50:49,353
I think that some Buddhist teachers... Yeah, I think...

528
00:50:49,554 --> 00:50:52,518
He just seemed to offer kind of alternative ways

529
00:50:53,039 --> 00:50:54,943
Well, you'd have to be... Yeah, that's it, you see.

530
00:50:54,963 --> 00:50:56,306
You'd have to make a... You'd have to...

531
00:50:56,708 --> 00:50:59,635
When you follow a path, you've got to make up your mind which path you're on.

532
00:51:00,356 --> 00:51:02,882
If you're a Krishnamurti, then get over there and do it.

533
00:51:03,344 --> 00:51:05,769
If you're on the Buddha's path, stay with the Buddha.

534
00:51:06,311 --> 00:51:06,972
It doesn't work.

535
00:51:07,074 --> 00:51:10,541
It doesn't work shifting...

536
00:51:10,943 --> 00:51:15,909
I know that you feel this.

537
00:51:15,929 --> 00:51:19,394
I know that you feel what you just said.

538
00:51:19,414 --> 00:51:20,496
I do.

539
00:51:20,516 --> 00:51:21,257
I don't feel it, is it?

540
00:51:21,478 --> 00:51:23,400
It's a fact.

541
00:51:23,601 --> 00:51:25,322
You say, I don't know.

542
00:51:25,342 --> 00:51:27,445
I mean, practice perhaps.

543
00:51:27,585 --> 00:51:33,153
I can really see the argument for committing to the practice at some point.

544
00:51:35,411 --> 00:51:49,253
Well, it's up to you.

545
00:51:49,293 --> 00:51:50,215
It's up to you, you see.

546
00:51:50,235 --> 00:51:56,103
I mean, to me, the great image of the spiritual path is climbing a mountain.

547
00:51:56,422 --> 00:51:58,806
If you want to go across the mountain to join another path, fine.

548
00:51:59,106 --> 00:52:01,692
But then you're going to have to learn new techniques because it's a different path.

549
00:52:02,534 --> 00:52:05,980
If you stay on the one path and you're quite certain it's going to the top, then you stay with it.

550
00:52:09,387 --> 00:52:10,710
I think that's what I meant.

551
00:52:10,730 --> 00:52:13,474
Do you have to... Do you have to follow a path?

552
00:52:13,494 --> 00:52:14,637
Can you just line the path?

553
00:52:15,097 --> 00:52:16,641
Does everybody have to ask a

554
00:52:18,764 --> 00:52:35,887
Well, you know, a technique is simply a trick to get that consciousness into a particular position so it can watch.

555
00:52:37,949 --> 00:52:39,092
That's all a technique is.

556
00:52:41,054 --> 00:52:47,943
So if your technique is to hit yourself on the head with a mallet every so often to come back into the present moment, fine, that'll do.

557
00:52:48,463 --> 00:52:49,005
It doesn't matter.

558
00:52:49,184 --> 00:52:51,509
There are as many techniques as there are teachers.

559
00:52:51,969 --> 00:52:59,900
The Mahasi technique really caught hold of the imagination, A, because of the clarity of his teaching.

560
00:52:59,960 --> 00:53:02,405
It's always clarity that draws people.

561
00:53:02,806 --> 00:53:07,853
Secondly, because at the time there was a real dearth of Vipassana meditation.

562
00:53:07,873 --> 00:53:08,474
It was quite new.

563
00:53:08,735 --> 00:53:15,585
The other person who came along was U Ba Khin, with the thing you did this afternoon with Christina.

564
00:53:15,565 --> 00:53:18,768
And there was a void there of vipassana teaching.

565
00:53:19,128 --> 00:53:20,911
And he had such a clarity about it.

566
00:53:20,931 --> 00:53:25,036
But more than that, he's one of these people who could get people to work.

567
00:53:25,056 --> 00:53:26,717
I mean, you hear this tape, four hours sleep.

568
00:53:27,458 --> 00:53:29,201
This isn't easy.

569
00:53:30,382 --> 00:53:31,985
That's the thing you've got to get across to yourself.

570
00:53:32,045 --> 00:53:32,746
It's not easy.

571
00:53:33,206 --> 00:53:38,012
You can't lie in the bath in the middle of nature and listen to the birds and become enlightened.

572
00:53:41,164 --> 00:53:42,827
At least, very difficult.

573
00:53:44,869 --> 00:53:45,190
Why?

574
00:53:45,231 --> 00:53:53,342
Because this consciousness is forever seeking happiness in the phenomenal world.

575
00:53:56,367 --> 00:53:58,731
That's the fundamental delusion about Dukkha.

576
00:53:58,831 --> 00:54:02,717
It's always seeking comfort in the phenomenal world.

577
00:54:04,639 --> 00:54:08,826
Therefore, the path necessarily is uncomfortable.

578
00:54:10,324 --> 00:54:13,469
If you go to a monastery and feel comfortable, nothing's happening.

579
00:54:15,253 --> 00:54:16,034
Nothing's happening.

580
00:54:18,217 --> 00:54:24,246
If you're meditating and you've spent a week and all you can say is, it was absolutely beautiful, I was blissed out, I was fine.

581
00:54:24,608 --> 00:54:31,759
When you come off a big pastoral retreat, the question is, what have I come to know?

582
00:54:31,820 --> 00:54:33,461
What have I come to know?

583
00:54:34,724 --> 00:54:35,304
What have I understood?

584
00:54:35,324 --> 00:54:35,826
What have I come to know?

585
00:54:38,775 --> 00:54:41,880
I don't want you to look so glum, Anneliese.

586
00:54:42,001 --> 00:54:42,722
I'm not.

587
00:54:42,742 --> 00:54:46,887
I've still got great questions for myself.

588
00:54:48,931 --> 00:54:53,018
So, Billy Darwin, I have a question here that we wrote down.

589
00:54:53,838 --> 00:55:03,753
We were talking earlier and we wanted to know what understanding of awareness, do you believe that awareness and consciousness are the same?

590
00:55:05,590 --> 00:55:07,172
Is that a question to me?

591
00:55:07,353 --> 00:55:09,556
Awareness and consciousness?

592
00:55:09,615 --> 00:55:16,746
Yeah, it's tradition, because Christina was saying that everyone, lots of slightly different traditions, view this very differently.

593
00:55:16,766 --> 00:55:18,730
I think most of the confusion is around words.

594
00:55:19,652 --> 00:55:25,000
And most of the confusion arises about what Nibbāna actually is.

595
00:55:25,822 --> 00:55:29,086
And if you look at the different schools, it splits into two.

596
00:55:29,126 --> 00:55:38,519
Even in Theravada you'll get the same split, like the people in northern Thailand, under Ajahn Mun, who Ajahn Chah was a sort of disciple.

597
00:55:38,539 --> 00:55:39,621
We'll talk about the Buddha.

598
00:55:39,782 --> 00:55:42,045
They'll talk about a level of consciousness.

599
00:55:42,846 --> 00:55:45,429
And you can point directly to the scripture and quote the Buddha.

600
00:55:45,630 --> 00:55:53,400
There is a non-manifestive consciousness, a consciousness without object.

601
00:55:53,936 --> 00:55:59,324
Without boundary and in all directions full of light.

602
00:55:59,344 --> 00:56:15,708
So you get those schools that tell you that the enlightenment is an actual living, live consciousness, which when it descends into the world of phenomena, in other words, being human beings, has a very different relationship to that world to the person who is not enlightened.

603
00:56:17,208 --> 00:56:20,590
Then you get the other school who think it's Nirodha Samapati.

604
00:56:20,971 --> 00:56:24,715
Now Nirodha Samapati is Sanya Vedana Nirodha Samapati.

605
00:56:25,155 --> 00:56:34,643
It's a state of, for want of a better word, unconsciousness, where all the ending of feeling and perception has gone.

606
00:56:34,664 --> 00:56:38,007
And it can only be got through the jhana.

607
00:56:38,806 --> 00:56:44,952
And it's only meant to be available to those people who are non-returners and the fully enlightened.

608
00:56:46,282 --> 00:56:50,961
and you'll get a whole load of people that tell you that Nibbāna is that state of nirodha.

609
00:56:54,215 --> 00:56:56,867
And it's difficult because the Buddha says

610
00:56:57,134 --> 00:57:03,304
When you have sensual pleasure, people think this is the highest happiness.

611
00:57:03,806 --> 00:57:08,152
But then they experience first jhāna, and they know that this sensual pleasure was quite low.

612
00:57:08,614 --> 00:57:10,257
First jhāna is the highest happiness.

613
00:57:10,918 --> 00:57:18,451
And then this way he takes you all the way up to the jhānas, and then he says, and when you come to the fourth jhāna, you flip into this nirodha samāpati.

614
00:57:18,831 --> 00:57:20,474
This is the highest happiness.

615
00:57:23,172 --> 00:57:35,784
So you're going to always have that argumentation in Buddhist schools as to what the actual end is, because for some reason the Buddha wasn't particularly clear on this one.

616
00:57:35,824 --> 00:57:38,186
He didn't make a complete statement, we can say.

617
00:57:38,947 --> 00:57:44,072
And to my mind, and the way it works for me is very simple.

618
00:57:45,273 --> 00:57:51,340
What you see in the universe, is it not, is a constant clicking off and on, isn't it?

619
00:57:51,606 --> 00:57:55,492
sleep and awakeness, winter and summer.

620
00:57:56,853 --> 00:58:00,318
Even moments are arising and passing away, arising and passing away.

621
00:58:00,800 --> 00:58:12,215
So for me, that consciousness can, as it were, step out of, into itself, in which case it does not experience itself as being in the phenomenal world.

622
00:58:14,257 --> 00:58:17,782
And it can also experience itself within the phenomenal world, awake.

623
00:58:18,994 --> 00:58:33,233
This on-off, on-off, rising-falling seems to be the fundamental movement within the whole of the universe, both at the phenomenal level and the spiritual level.

624
00:58:33,253 --> 00:58:38,820
So the battle is always between death and birth, and death and birth.

625
00:58:41,003 --> 00:58:48,934
And this suffering arises because this consciousness has simply identified with the phenomenal world of feeling, sensation, etc.,

626
00:58:52,795 --> 00:58:56,619
So it depends on which school you want to belong to, where you want to go.

627
00:58:56,681 --> 00:58:59,324
But for me, in a sense, that's all sort of endgame.

628
00:58:59,684 --> 00:59:04,532
